<h2>Online Learning</h2>
Are you looking for opportunities to learn more about parent involvement? Check out these free resources to build your skills.
<ul>
	<li><a href="http://www.thirteen.org/edonline/concept2class/familycommunity/index.html">Making Family and Community Connections</a> is a self-paced online workshop for teachers, which provides a good introduction to parent involvement, based on Epstein&#8217;s Six Types of Involvement.</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.tcet.unt.edu/pteconnect/">Parent Teacher Education Connection</a> includes six online modules based on the National PTA Standards and designed to support pre-service and in-service teacher development of cross-cultural competence in engaging parent involvement in the learning of K-12 students.</li>
	<li><a href="http://www1.cyfernet.org/onlinepd.html">Children, Youth, and Families Education and Research Network</a> offers interactive online training sessions and webinars on a variety of topics including parent involvement. Past sessions are archived. </li>
	<li><a href="http://www.sedl.org/learning/">Modules for Community and Family Involvement with Schools</a> review emerging findings and research in the area of family and community involvement with schools in three interactive strategy briefs, which are available in English and Spanish.</li>
	<li><a href="http://literacynetwork.verizon.org/tln/courses">Thinkfinity Literacy Network's Online Courses</a> guide educators, program managers, students and volunteers in the best literacy instruction and lifelong learning habits.</li>
</ul>
